====================================================================
üìå CANDIDATE KEY IN DBMS (NOTES + EXAMPLES)
====================================================================

A CANDIDATE KEY is a **minimal Super Key** that can
**uniquely identify a record** in a table.

It contains **NO extra attributes**.

====================================================================
WHY DO WE USE CANDIDATE KEY?
--------------------------------------------------------------------
‚úî To uniquely identify each record  
‚úî To choose the Primary Key  
‚úî To avoid redundancy  
‚úî To maintain data integrity  

====================================================================
DEFINITION (EXAM READY)
--------------------------------------------------------------------
A Candidate Key is a **minimal set of attributes**
that uniquely identifies each tuple in a relation.

====================================================================
EXAMPLE TABLE: STUDENT
--------------------------------------------------------------------
| Roll_No | Aadhaar | Email | Name |
--------------------------------------------------------------------

Candidate Keys:
--------------------------------------------------------------------
‚úî {Roll_No}  
‚úî {Aadhaar}  
‚úî {Email}  

‚ùå NOT Candidate Keys:
--------------------------------------------------------------------
{Roll_No, Name}  ‚Üí extra attribute  
{Aadhaar, Name}  ‚Üí not minimal  

====================================================================
CANDIDATE KEY vs SUPER KEY
--------------------------------------------------------------------
‚úî Super Key:
   ‚Üí May contain extra attributes  
   ‚Üí Not minimal  

‚úî Candidate Key:
   ‚Üí Minimal Super Key  
   ‚Üí No unnecessary attributes  

Example:
{Roll_No, Name} ‚Üí Super Key  
{Roll_No} ‚Üí Candidate Key  

====================================================================
CANDIDATE KEY vs PRIMARY KEY
--------------------------------------------------------------------
‚úî Candidate Key:
   ‚Üí Many possible in a table  
   ‚Üí Can contain NULL (theoretically)  

‚úî Primary Key:
   ‚Üí Only ONE per table  
   ‚Üí Cannot be NULL  
   ‚Üí Selected from Candidate Keys  

====================================================================
IMPORTANT RULES
--------------------------------------------------------------------
‚úî Every Candidate Key is a Super Key  
‚úî Primary Key is chosen from Candidate Keys  
‚úî A table can have multiple Candidate Keys  
‚úî Candidate Keys are unique & minimal  

====================================================================
REAL-LIFE EXAMPLE
--------------------------------------------------------------------
ATM CARD SYSTEM:
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Card_Number, Account_Number, Aadhaar

Candidate Keys:
‚úî Card_Number  
‚úî Account_Number  
‚úî Aadhaar  

Primary Key:
‚úî Card_Number (chosen by DB designer)

====================================================================
SUMMARY
====================================================================
‚úî Candidate Key = Minimal Super Key  
‚úî Uniquely identifies records  
‚úî Used to select Primary Key  
‚úî Fundamental concept in DBMS  

END OF NOTES
====================================================================
